      <div class="msgContentFrame">Well, ya.  See...ya... <br /> <br />Provoke is not a threat tool.  I know a lot of Gladiators (and any other tank class, for that matter) hate being told that, but it's the truth.  It's not XI, guy.  Provoke serves a different purpose in XIV and from everything I've been reading, people are finally starting to realize that the actual enmity gain from Provoke is pretty trivial.   <br /> <br />In other MMOs, abilities like Taunt and Provoke are used to pull a mob back to you if it runs off after someone else in the party.  Occasionally it's used to swap tanks in single-target, multi-tank encounters.  SE appears to have taken a look at that and decided that that's the model they want to run with instead of just Provoke = enmity spike and that is all.  The actual enmity gain seems more to give you a bit of a boost in overtaking the enmity of the person who peeled the mob, not to build enmity to try and stick the mob to you. <br /> <br />If you're using Provoke every time it's off cooldown, you're wasting stamina.  Stop and think about the other things you could have done with that stamina that might have actually built more enmity.  Not only that, but Provoke doesn't give you any TP.  And lastly...and this could wind up being the wipe-causer later on...if you're using Provoke as an enmity tool, what do you do 6 seconds later when you've whiffed your last three attacks and your healer peels the mob? <br /> <br />If you're in a PUG group or your LS is full of a bunch of dimwits that refuse to give you a few seconds off the pull to generate some threat before they go nuts, then by all means start with Provoke and use the Provoked debuff to buy you the time that you need but understand that you're better off educating people to play a smarter game than to be blowing 40% of your stamina off the top just to stick a mob to you for 3-5 seconds. <br /> <br />If you're pacing your attacks properly and using your abilities appropriately, stamina isn't that big of an issue for Gladiators.  Alternating between Light (Heavy) Slash/Stab + Phalanx (which uses no stamina) + Guard + weapon skills is not all that taxing on your stamina bar.  And if you manage your stamina bar you should always have plenty of stamina for contingency abilities like defensive cooldowns and...Provoke.</div>
